00:03:40.110 --> 00:03:43.200
And I think that we get stuck
between this idea of being

00:03:43.200 --> 00:03:46.910
a go-getter, which all of us
probably in this room are,

00:03:46.910 --> 00:03:48.180
and being gutsy.

00:03:48.180 --> 00:03:50.880
Those are two very
different things.

00:03:50.880 --> 00:03:53.340
Gutsy means I'm going to
take a risk at something,

00:03:53.340 --> 00:03:57.220
and it's probably not
going to work out.

00:03:57.220 --> 00:03:59.380
But I'm going to do it anyway.

00:03:59.380 --> 00:04:03.000
So like for me, I, my whole
life, was a go-getter.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:06.570
I went to the right schools,
worked at the right places.

00:04:06.570 --> 00:04:09.400
I always, quote, "signed
up for things," but things

00:04:09.400 --> 00:04:12.960
that I knew that I
could execute perfectly.

00:04:12.960 --> 00:04:17.680
I didn't become gutsy until
I ran for Congress at age 33

00:04:17.680 --> 00:04:19.680
against someone who had
been there for 18 years.

00:04:19.680 --> 00:04:22.380
And I pretty much had
no chance of winning.

00:04:22.380 --> 00:04:25.230
That's when everything
changed for me.

00:04:25.230 --> 00:04:28.380
Because before that, I
thought that if I failed,

00:04:28.380 --> 00:04:31.740
I would literally break,
that it would hurt me

00:04:31.740 --> 00:04:34.710
so much that I wouldn't
be able to recover.

00:04:34.710 --> 00:04:36.960
And when I failed at something
and it didn't break me,

00:04:36.960 --> 00:04:39.480
I was like, OK, I can
live my life this way.

00:04:39.480 --> 00:04:43.778
I can continue to be
a gutsy go-getter.

00:04:43.778 --> 00:04:45.570
JASON SPERO: Could you
tell us a little bit

00:04:45.570 --> 00:04:47.870
about your journey which
led you to run to Congress

00:04:47.870 --> 00:04:49.537
and the things that
happened after that?

00:04:49.537 --> 00:04:52.470
RESHMA SAUJANI: Yeah, so my
parents came here as refugees.

00:04:52.470 --> 00:04:54.960
And I was like the
quintessential good Indian

00:04:54.960 --> 00:04:56.070
girl.

00:04:56.070 --> 00:04:57.390
You know what I mean?

00:04:57.390 --> 00:05:01.170
I did everything that
I was supposed to do.

00:05:01.170 --> 00:05:02.740
I went to the right schools.

00:05:02.740 --> 00:05:03.660
I got A's.

00:05:03.660 --> 00:05:05.630
I didn't get into
cars with boys.

00:05:05.630 --> 00:05:06.990
All the things, right?

00:05:06.990 --> 00:05:08.070
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:08.070 --> 00:05:09.390
I didn't do those.

00:05:09.390 --> 00:05:14.830
I lived the perfect Indian girl
life, all in search of a better

00:05:14.830 --> 00:05:15.330
me.

00:05:15.330 --> 00:05:19.440
A more perfect me would make
a more happier Mom and Dad.

00:05:19.440 --> 00:05:22.860
And I also thought that,
well, if I was perfect,

00:05:22.860 --> 00:05:27.000
I would be happy and that if I
kept moving through the success

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:29.100
culture and getting
those accolades that it

00:05:29.100 --> 00:05:31.290
would make me happier.

00:05:31.290 --> 00:05:35.910
And so I graduated $300,000
in student loan debt, right?

00:05:35.910 --> 00:05:39.020
I thought I would work at one
of those finance law firms,

00:05:39.020 --> 00:05:40.770
and I would pay off
that student loan debt

00:05:40.770 --> 00:05:41.687
in like a year or two.

00:05:41.687 --> 00:05:43.810
And then I could do what
I really wanted to do,

00:05:43.810 --> 00:05:46.560
which was run for office
and be a public servant.

00:05:46.560 --> 00:05:47.960
Two years turned into 10.

00:05:47.960 --> 00:05:52.350
Then I woke up at age 33 working
as a lawyer on a trading floor,

00:05:52.350 --> 00:05:54.990
coming home every day
in the fetal position

00:05:54.990 --> 00:05:57.870
to a very large bottle of wine.

00:05:57.870 --> 00:06:00.420
I hated my job.

00:06:00.420 --> 00:06:02.280
I remember I was
sitting there one day.

00:06:02.280 --> 00:06:05.000
And my best friend
Deepa calls me.

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:06.750
And it's funny how
your best friend always

00:06:06.750 --> 00:06:09.080
calls you when your life
is like falling apart.

00:06:09.080 --> 00:06:10.250
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:10.250 --> 00:06:11.250
And I go into this room.

00:06:11.250 --> 00:06:12.250
And I just start crying.

00:06:12.250 --> 00:06:16.020
And she just says,
Reshma, just quit.

00:06:16.020 --> 00:06:18.720
And I was like,
(WHISPERING) I can do that?

00:06:18.720 --> 00:06:19.290
And I quit.

00:06:19.290 --> 00:06:21.540
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:21.540 --> 00:06:23.935
I said, all right.

00:06:23.935 --> 00:06:24.810
I'm going to do this.

00:06:24.810 --> 00:06:26.930
And I ran for Congress.

00:06:26.930 --> 00:06:29.395
I was the first Indian
American woman to run.

00:06:29.395 --> 00:06:31.770
I remember the only thing my
friends and I knew how to do

00:06:31.770 --> 00:06:32.760
was build a website.

00:06:32.760 --> 00:06:33.510
And we built one.

00:06:33.510 --> 00:06:36.410
And we raised like $50,000
from Indian aunties

00:06:36.410 --> 00:06:38.160
that were just so happy
an Indian girl was

00:06:38.160 --> 00:06:38.980
running for office.

00:06:38.980 --> 00:06:41.010
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:41.010 --> 00:06:47.040
But it was the best experience
of my life, because I was free.

00:06:47.040 --> 00:06:50.910
And I got crushed in that race.

00:06:50.910 --> 00:06:54.990
I raised like $1.4 million, and
I got like a thousand votes.

00:06:54.990 --> 00:06:55.950
Don't do the math.

00:06:55.950 --> 00:06:58.360
It was really bad.

00:06:58.360 --> 00:06:59.080
I was broke.

00:06:59.080 --> 00:07:01.110
I was humiliated.

00:07:01.110 --> 00:07:02.250
I felt ashamed.

00:07:02.250 --> 00:07:03.300
People felt sorry for me.

00:07:03.300 --> 00:07:04.467
And I'm one of those people.

00:07:04.467 --> 00:07:07.390
I hate when people
feel sorry for me.

00:07:07.390 --> 00:07:12.630
But I was able to
recover from that.

00:07:12.630 --> 00:07:15.965
And drink a lot of
margaritas for like a month,

00:07:15.965 --> 00:07:18.090
ask my boyfriend who's now
my husband over and over

00:07:18.090 --> 00:07:18.990
again, what happened?

00:07:18.990 --> 00:07:19.573
What happened?

00:07:19.573 --> 00:07:20.560
What happened?

00:07:20.560 --> 00:07:23.760
And then I was
like, OK, I'm alive.

00:07:23.760 --> 00:07:25.380
I'm ready for my next fight.

00:07:25.380 --> 00:07:29.100
And it changed my entire life.

00:07:29.100 --> 00:07:29.790
It's funny.

00:07:29.790 --> 00:07:33.690
That experience led me
to start Girls Who Code.

00:07:33.690 --> 00:07:36.210
And I didn't even code.

00:07:36.210 --> 00:07:37.980
Think about how crazy that was.

00:07:37.980 --> 00:07:40.680
But it was because of
the bravery of that race

00:07:40.680 --> 00:07:42.780
and not winning it
and it not breaking me

00:07:42.780 --> 00:07:45.300
that I thought that I could
actually start something

00:07:45.300 --> 00:07:47.220
that I wasn't an expert on.

00:07:47.220 --> 00:07:49.590
And I think that's the power
of "Brave, Not Perfect."

00:07:49.590 --> 00:07:51.840
That's the power of
letting go of perfectionism

00:07:51.840 --> 00:07:54.880
and rewriting yourself and
living a life of bravery.

00:07:54.880 --> 00:07:56.900
It opens your life
up to so much.

00:07:56.900 --> 00:07:58.650
JASON SPERO: There's
a phrase in the book.

00:07:58.650 --> 00:08:01.305
You said, "I'm lost,
