moment of strength that

00:08:03.180 --> 00:08:05.180
comes from the losing
that you're talking about.

00:08:05.180 --> 00:08:06.790
And you use the word
resilience a lot.

00:08:06.790 --> 00:08:07.500
RESHMA SAUJANI: Yeah.

00:08:07.500 --> 00:08:08.910
JASON SPERO: What can
people just-- maybe

00:08:08.910 --> 00:08:11.160
bring it back for a minute
to the people in this room.

00:08:11.160 --> 00:08:13.430
Where does resilience come
into play in everyday life

00:08:13.430 --> 00:08:15.530
for people who might
be in this room today?

00:08:15.530 --> 00:08:17.340
RESHMA SAUJANI: Yeah, so we all
got to throw out the parenting

00:08:17.340 --> 00:08:18.030
books.

00:08:18.030 --> 00:08:20.490
I know this sounds
dramatic, but I'm serious.

00:08:20.490 --> 00:08:22.620
The way that many of
us have been raised

00:08:22.620 --> 00:08:24.360
has just been wrong.

00:08:24.360 --> 00:08:27.960
So many of us, our parents
protected us, right?

00:08:27.960 --> 00:08:29.730
So if we were bad
at soccer, they

00:08:29.730 --> 00:08:32.400
would pull us out and
put us into gymnastics.

00:08:32.400 --> 00:08:37.570
They never wanted us to feel
fear or rejection or failure.

00:08:37.570 --> 00:08:39.870
They were constantly
trying to protect us.

00:08:39.870 --> 00:08:43.140
And so we didn't know what
it was like to, basically,

00:08:43.140 --> 00:08:44.250
be challenged.

00:08:44.250 --> 00:08:46.500
And many times, many of us,
when we were little girls,

00:08:46.500 --> 00:08:47.880
we would walk away
something that

00:08:47.880 --> 00:08:49.560
didn't come to us right away.

00:08:49.560 --> 00:08:51.090
And we would walk
away thinking, oh,

00:08:51.090 --> 00:08:56.350
if math isn't coming to me right
away, I must not be good at it.

00:08:56.350 --> 00:08:58.890
And we thought that our
mindset was fixed rather

00:08:58.890 --> 00:09:01.060
than we had a growth mindset.

00:09:01.060 --> 00:09:04.180
And so I think that we have
to unlearn all of that.

00:09:04.180 --> 00:09:06.990
So in the search of our parents
trying to build us confidence,

00:09:06.990 --> 00:09:09.300
they killed our
resilience, literally

00:09:09.300 --> 00:09:10.950
killed our resilience.

00:09:10.950 --> 00:09:13.410
And so many of us
find ourselves in jobs

00:09:13.410 --> 00:09:17.790
that we feel eh about
but won't walk away.

00:09:17.790 --> 00:09:20.140
We find ourselves in
relationships, quite frankly,

00:09:20.140 --> 00:09:21.270
that are broken.

00:09:21.270 --> 00:09:23.730
But we're too
scared to walk away.

00:09:23.730 --> 00:09:25.320
Many of us were
probably walking down

00:09:25.320 --> 00:09:27.870
the street last week and
someone bumped into you.

00:09:27.870 --> 00:09:32.220
And you said, I'm sorry, right?

00:09:32.220 --> 00:09:35.735
And then you went home and
you're like mad at yourself

00:09:35.735 --> 00:09:37.110
for not sticking
up for yourself.

00:09:37.110 --> 00:09:40.680
Because we don't know how.

00:09:40.680 --> 00:09:42.640
We haven't been taught.

00:09:42.640 --> 00:09:45.890
And it's the complete
opposite with our boys.

00:09:45.890 --> 00:09:48.100
In the quest to teach
our boys how to be men,

00:09:48.100 --> 00:09:49.850
how to be fearless,
how to be risk takers,

00:09:49.850 --> 00:09:52.850
how to be tough so they
can survive in this world,

00:09:52.850 --> 00:09:55.190
we constantly expose
them to challenges.

00:09:55.190 --> 00:09:57.110
We constantly push
them on the edge.

00:09:57.110 --> 00:09:59.180
We constantly give
them negative feedback

00:09:59.180 --> 00:10:02.150
over and over and over again
to build their resiliency.

00:10:02.150 --> 00:10:03.860
And we didn't do
that for our girls,

00:10:03.860 --> 00:10:07.160
and so we haven't learned how
to operate in a world that

00:10:07.160 --> 00:10:10.328
does not reward perfection.

