00:10:38.820 --> 00:10:39.320
Who Code.

00:10:39.320 --> 00:10:40.695
RESHMA SAUJANI:
Here's the thing.

00:10:40.695 --> 00:10:44.570
I think that-- so a lot of
our girls, half our girls,

00:10:44.570 --> 00:10:46.200
are under the poverty line.

00:10:46.200 --> 00:10:48.380
Half our girls are
black and Latina.

00:10:48.380 --> 00:10:51.410
And so it's this amazing
mix of young women.

00:10:51.410 --> 00:10:53.120
We live in a country
whose schools

00:10:53.120 --> 00:10:56.390
are so segregated that
what I wanted to build

00:10:56.390 --> 00:10:58.490
was classrooms that
look like America.

00:10:58.490 --> 00:11:00.320
Because I thought that
if we actually built

00:11:00.320 --> 00:11:02.360
sisterhood together
that we could

00:11:02.360 --> 00:11:06.860
build the most amazing
future products together.

00:11:06.860 --> 00:11:08.622
And what's powerful is that--

00:11:08.622 --> 00:11:10.580
so a lot of our girls
come because their mother

00:11:10.580 --> 00:11:11.682
drags them.

00:11:11.682 --> 00:11:12.890
Their grandmother drags them.

00:11:12.890 --> 00:11:14.600
Their librarian talks about it.

00:11:14.600 --> 00:11:16.600
Their parents are just
trying to get rid of them

00:11:16.600 --> 00:11:18.290
for the summer to do something.

00:11:18.290 --> 00:11:20.590
So they don't walk in
being like, god, I'm

00:11:20.590 --> 00:11:22.730
a kick butt coder, right?

00:11:22.730 --> 00:11:25.190
They actually have a
lot of insecurities

00:11:25.190 --> 00:11:26.900
about their ability.

00:11:26.900 --> 00:11:28.532
And this book and
this talk really

00:11:28.532 --> 00:11:29.990
started from the
same story I would

00:11:29.990 --> 00:11:33.392
hear about how when girls were
first learning how to code,

00:11:33.392 --> 00:11:35.600
they basically would call
their teacher over and say,

00:11:35.600 --> 00:11:37.485
I don't know what code to write.

00:11:37.485 --> 00:11:39.110
And the teacher would
look at a screen,

00:11:39.110 --> 00:11:41.790
and she'd see a
blank text editor.

00:11:41.790 --> 00:11:43.280
So if she didn't
know any better,

00:11:43.280 --> 00:11:45.980
she thought, well, my
student spent 20 minutes just

00:11:45.980 --> 00:11:48.290
staring at the screen.

00:11:48.290 --> 00:11:51.050
But when she pressed
Undo a few times,

00:11:51.050 --> 00:11:52.940
she saw that her
student actually wrote

00:11:52.940 --> 00:11:56.460
code and then deleted it.

00:11:56.460 --> 00:11:59.240
So instead of saying, hey, look
at the progress that I made,

00:11:59.240 --> 00:12:02.240
she'd rather show
her nothing at all.

00:12:02.240 --> 00:12:04.250
So when girls actually
learn how to code,

00:12:04.250 --> 00:12:07.940
it's as if they've learned
a superpower that opens up

00:12:07.940 --> 00:12:12.170
their entire life to doing
things that they thought

00:12:12.170 --> 00:12:14.630
that they couldn't
do, to stopping

00:12:14.630 --> 00:12:17.720
giving up before they even try.

00:12:17.720 --> 00:12:20.930
And I think that that's the
beauty and the power of coding.

00:12:20.930 --> 00:12:22.950
Girls Who Code, it's
so much more than that.

00:12:22.950 --> 00:12:26.540
There was this powerful
article in the "New York Times"

00:12:26.540 --> 00:12:28.890
last week about,
how did we get here?

00:12:28.890 --> 00:12:31.490
How did we get to a world
where we had 40% of women

00:12:31.490 --> 00:12:34.190
in computer science, where we
had Ada Lovelace, ENIAC women,

00:12:34.190 --> 00:12:37.940
Katherine Johnson, to
here, where we barely

00:12:37.940 --> 00:12:40.850
can get 18% of our
workforce being female?

00:12:40.850 --> 00:12:43.640
And don't get me started on
black and Latina numbers.

00:12:43.640 --> 00:12:45.750
How did we get there?

00:12:45.750 --> 00:12:48.920
And part of how we got
there was that essentially,

00:12:48.920 --> 00:12:52.890
in the 1980s, parents started
giving computers to boys.

00:12:52.890 --> 00:12:56.090
And so it became something that
they tinkered, and they played,

00:12:56.090 --> 00:12:56.990
took apart.

00:12:56.990 --> 00:12:59.060
And so when they came
in the classroom,

00:12:59.060 --> 00:13:02.900
it was as if the boys were
coming in with an experience

00:13:02.900 --> 00:13:04.730
that the girls didn't have.

00:13:04.730 --> 00:13:06.440
And then the girls
started questioning

00:13:06.440 --> 00:13:09.350
not their ability
but their perceived

00:13:09.350 --> 00:13:11.480
ability in their head.

00:13:11.480 --> 00:13:16.220
And they started dropping
out one by one by one by one.

00:13:16.220 --> 00:13:18.770
It's never about what we can do.

00:13:18.770 --> 00:13:20.900
It's always about
what we think we

00:13:20.900 --> 00:13:23.120
can do, that voice in
our head that tells us

00:13:23.120 --> 00:13:25.820
that we're not good enough,
that we're not smart enough.

00:13:25.820 --> 00:13:30.050
We go very quickly from,
this is hard, to, I suck.

00:13:30.050 --> 00:13:31.110
I'm not smart.

00:13:31.110 --> 00:13:32.960
I've got to go do
something else.

00:13:32.960 --> 00:13:36.260
And that, to me, is the
opportunity of Girls

00:13:36.260 --> 00:13:40.160
Who Code right now in that,
we've taught a lot of girls.

00:13:40.160 --> 00:13:42.800
Now I got to get you to
believe in yourself so

00:13:42.800 --> 00:13:47.060
that when it starts getting
tough, because it always will,

00:13:47.060 --> 00:13:48.280
you can stick with it.

00:13:48.280 --> 00:13:50.030
JASON SPERO: And I
think one of the things

00:13:50.030 --> 00:13:52.523
that you've taught
me is it's not just

00:13:52.523 --> 00:13:54.440
about getting someone
and getting them curious

00:13:54.440 --> 00:13:56.210
in third, fourth, fifth grade.

00:13:56.210 --> 00:13:58.430
But that stick
with it as they go

00:13:58.430 --> 00:14:01.130
based on all the social
signals in the first year CS

00:14:01.130 --> 00:14:03.122
class in university
and all the things

00:14:03.122 --> 00:14:04.580
that come after
that, which I think

00:14:04.580 --> 00:14:07.340
connects it back to a problem
we talk about a lot of Google.

00:14:07.340 --> 00:14:10.280
Which is, where is that
talent pool so that Google

00:14:10.280 --> 00:14:12.770
can shift the gender balance?

00:14:12.770 --> 00:14:14.270
So can you talk
just about the Girls

00:14:14.270 --> 00:14:17.390
Who Code mission from the
deleting code and the "I

00:14:17.390 --> 00:14:21.657
can't do this" at the micro,
but to that 15, 20 year journey?

00:14:21.657 --> 00:14:23.240
RESHMA SAUJANI: Yeah,
that's powerful.

00:14:23.240 --> 00:14:25.282
Like a story on that when
I was doing my TEDTalk,

00:14:25.282 --> 00:14:27.350
one of my friends
who's a CS teacher

00:14:27.350 --> 00:14:30.440
was saying, when the guys are
struggling with the assignment,

00:14:30.440 --> 00:14:32.930
they'll literally come into
office hours and be like, dude,

00:14:32.930 --> 00:14:34.340
the computer's broken.

00:14:34.340 --> 00:14:37.187
The computer is broken, right?

00:14:37.187 --> 00:14:39.020
And women will come and
be like, I'm broken.

00:14:39.020 --> 00:14:41.450
There's something wrong with me.

00:14:41.450 --> 00:14:45.020
And this happens all
throughout the pipeline.

00:14:45.020 --> 00:14:50.060
And so look, I think last year
this country graduated almost

00:14:50.060 --> 00:14:52.670
40,000-50,000 computer
science graduates,

00:14:52.670 --> 00:14:55.250
of which 10,000 to
12,000 were women.

00:14:55.250 --> 00:14:59.400
We have 500,000 open jobs
in computing and technology.

00:14:59.400 --> 00:15:01.363
And so we got a lot
of jobs to fill.

00:15:01.363 --> 00:15:02.780
And we're living
in a moment where

00:15:02.780 --> 00:15:04.883
40% of America's
breadwinners are women.

00:15:04.883 --> 00:15:07.550
So women are putting food on the
table, paying for the mortgage.

00:15:07.550 --> 00:15:09.920
So we've got to get
them into these jobs.

00:15:09.920 --> 00:15:12.170
Girls Who Code, by the
end of 2019, will have

00:15:12.170 --> 00:15:14.450
reached 185,000 girls.

00:15:14.450 --> 00:15:17.570
Now, I'm not talking about
tinkering with a little code

00:15:17.570 --> 00:15:19.430
and making the
sprite make a square.

00:15:19.430 --> 00:15:23.990
I mean actually
teaching girls to code.

00:15:23.990 --> 00:15:26.958
There is a difference
between exposure and access

00:15:26.958 --> 00:15:27.500
and teaching.

00:15:27.500 --> 00:15:29.630
And we need to get
very clear about that

00:15:29.630 --> 00:15:32.040
as we're thinking about
how we solve the problem.

00:15:32.040 --> 00:15:34.790
So I am confident that
we have enough of you

00:15:34.790 --> 00:15:37.800
amazing young women coming
through the pipeline.

00:15:37.800 --> 00:15:40.550
Now the question is, are
you going to hire them?

00:15:40.550 --> 00:15:43.970
Are you going to hire them?

00:15:43.970 --> 00:15:47.630
We know that processes
are so broken.

00:15:47.630 --> 00:15:50.690
I face this as a CEO
of an organization.

00:15:50.690 --> 00:15:54.660
We can't assume that our hiring
processes are equitable, fair,

00:15:54.660 --> 00:15:56.720
and just, especially
when we've had

00:15:56.720 --> 00:16:01.460
only one type of person come
through the hiring pipeline.

00:16:01.460 --> 00:16:04.885
We have to be intentional
about who we want to see.

00:16:04.885 --> 00:16:06.260
And so that's the
work that we're

00:16:06.260 --> 00:16:08.390
trying to do at Girls Who Code.

00:16:08.390 --> 00:16:11.747
We've launched 300 College
Loops on college campuses,

00:16:11.747 --> 00:16:13.580
because the vast majority
of young women who

00:16:13.580 --> 00:16:16.130
are majoring in CS on
campuses across the country

00:16:16.130 --> 00:16:19.630
are ours, our Girls Who Code.

00:16:19.630 --> 00:16:23.770
And so now I've got to make sure
that 50% of them don't drop out

00:16:23.770 --> 00:16:26.860
and that college universities
have as broken, sexist,

00:16:26.860 --> 00:16:28.060
and racist structures--

00:16:28.060 --> 00:16:29.320
I'm sure some of the
women in this room

00:16:29.320 --> 00:16:31.653
that have gone through them
before know exactly what I'm

00:16:31.653 --> 00:16:33.770
talking about, as do companies.

00:16:33.770 --> 00:16:36.220
So we have work to
do there to change

00:16:36.220 --> 00:16:38.410
that, to change
that mentality of,

00:16:38.410 --> 00:16:40.092
we're just going
to root you out.

00:16:40.092 --> 00:16:42.550
And then we need to work with
our companies who, I believe,

00:16:42.550 --> 00:16:47.410
are truly committed to this
issue, to say, OK, maybe

00:16:47.410 --> 00:16:50.890
we need to stop looking
at the same eight colleges

00:16:50.890 --> 00:16:55.045
for the same group of women,
especially in a moment where,

00:16:55.045 --> 00:16:56.940
because of the
student loan crisis,

00:16:56.940 --> 00:16:58.760
many parents are not
confident to say,

00:16:58.760 --> 00:17:01.360
all right, sweetie, go take
$300,000 in student loan debt.

00:17:01.360 --> 00:17:03.010
It's all going to be OK.

00:17:03.010 --> 00:17:04.550
Things have changed.

00:17:04.550 --> 00:17:06.770
And so we have to figure
out they're there.

00:17:06.770 --> 00:17:08.510
Do we want to find them?

00:17:08.510 --> 00:17:09.720
Do we want to find them?

00:17:09.720 --> 00:17:12.220
JASON SPERO: And that's about
finding them and sourcing them

00:17:12.220 --> 00:17:13.430
into an interview process.

00:17:13.430 --> 00:17:15.160
