00:21:16.630 --> 00:21:19.550
That is the power of women
coming up and saying,

00:21:19.550 --> 00:21:21.380
enough is enough.

00:21:21.380 --> 00:21:24.130
We won't let you write us out.

00:21:24.130 --> 00:21:26.418
We won't, not anymore.

00:21:26.418 --> 00:21:28.210
And I think one of the
most powerful things

00:21:28.210 --> 00:21:31.690
about the internet is
about the ability for us

00:21:31.690 --> 00:21:33.400
to then come together
no matter where

00:21:33.400 --> 00:21:38.390
we are to lift each other
up and to say what's right.

00:21:38.390 --> 00:21:40.050
JASON SPERO: Related
to that decision

00:21:40.050 --> 00:21:41.900
to call out "60
Minutes," can you tell me

00:21:41.900 --> 00:21:44.640
about the difference
between "this is hard"

00:21:44.640 --> 00:21:46.500
and "I can't do this?"

00:21:46.500 --> 00:21:48.920
RESHMA SAUJANI: Yeah, I think
the thing is it is natural

00:21:48.920 --> 00:21:54.830
to feel that something is hard
to do and then to feel like

00:21:54.830 --> 00:21:55.580
that I can't.

00:21:55.580 --> 00:21:59.540
Because I can't feels like
it comes from your ability.

00:21:59.540 --> 00:22:04.640
And I think, oftentimes, we
start questioning our ability.

00:22:04.640 --> 00:22:08.540
Because athletes,
like athletes often

00:22:08.540 --> 00:22:11.390
sit on the edge of
their critical feedback

00:22:11.390 --> 00:22:12.170
and their ability.

00:22:12.170 --> 00:22:14.540
So there's a coach that is
sitting there and constantly

00:22:14.540 --> 00:22:15.990
saying, do it again.

00:22:15.990 --> 00:22:16.920
Do it again.

00:22:16.920 --> 00:22:18.040
Do it again.

00:22:18.040 --> 00:22:21.560
Oftentimes, for
us, because we've

00:22:21.560 --> 00:22:24.960
been coddled and protected, we
haven't gotten that feedback,

00:22:24.960 --> 00:22:25.460
right?

00:22:25.460 --> 00:22:29.480
So we haven't been able to
build our muscles in the way

00:22:29.480 --> 00:22:31.682
that we need to
build our muscles.

00:22:31.682 --> 00:22:33.140
And so I think we
immediately think

00:22:33.140 --> 00:22:35.220
that we're either good
or bad at something.

00:22:35.220 --> 00:22:37.790
And that's not the
way that things work.

00:22:37.790 --> 00:22:41.480
You have to learn how to
practice and build it up.

00:22:41.480 --> 00:22:43.127
JASON SPERO: All
right, yes, please?

00:22:43.127 --> 00:22:45.710
AUDIENCE: Hi, I was wondering
if you could go back and tell us

00:22:45.710 --> 00:22:49.790
about how you ended up creating
a very successful organization

00:22:49.790 --> 00:22:52.062
in something you didn't
even have experience in?

00:22:52.062 --> 00:22:54.020
RESHMA SAUJANI: Yeah, so
it's one of the things

00:22:54.020 --> 00:22:58.910
actually I write about in the
book about this idea of just

00:22:58.910 --> 00:23:00.170
starting.

00:23:00.170 --> 00:23:03.630
So here I am, day after
election, I'm crushed.

00:23:03.630 --> 00:23:04.250
I'm broke.

00:23:04.250 --> 00:23:05.150
I'm humiliated.

00:23:05.150 --> 00:23:06.560
I've pissed off everybody.

00:23:06.560 --> 00:23:09.020
Nobody's calling me
for a job, right?

00:23:09.020 --> 00:23:12.680
I am surprised that
I'm still functioning.

00:23:12.680 --> 00:23:15.860
And it was very clear to me
that those 10 months of my life

00:23:15.860 --> 00:23:20.520
were the best 10 months of
my life and that I was happy.

00:23:20.520 --> 00:23:24.390
So I'm like, OK, I'm not going
back to the private sector.

00:23:24.390 --> 00:23:27.915
And I said, all right, of
all the things that I saw,

00:23:27.915 --> 00:23:29.540
where's the place
that I actually think

00:23:29.540 --> 00:23:31.100
that I can make a difference?

00:23:31.100 --> 00:23:33.500
And I kept thinking
about those classrooms

00:23:33.500 --> 00:23:37.640
that I would walk into where
I wouldn't see any girls.

00:23:37.640 --> 00:23:39.380
And I don't know about you guys.

00:23:39.380 --> 00:23:42.800
But I always have a job
and then a night hustle,

00:23:42.800 --> 00:23:46.010
like the thing that I'm
working on on the side.

00:23:46.010 --> 00:23:48.860
And I'm a lawyer, so
I love to research.

00:23:48.860 --> 00:23:52.347
So I started just looking at
why are there not women in tech?

00:23:52.347 --> 00:23:53.180
Where are the girls?

00:23:53.180 --> 00:23:54.650
What are the programs?

00:23:54.650 --> 00:23:58.820
And I would spend my lunch
hours and my nights meeting

00:23:58.820 --> 00:24:01.490
with people, principals
who taught computer science

00:24:01.490 --> 00:24:03.950
classrooms, PhDs who
were trying to understand

00:24:03.950 --> 00:24:06.800
this problem, people
who ran nonprofits.

00:24:06.800 --> 00:24:09.810
And so two years
in, I was like, OK,

00:24:09.810 --> 00:24:13.650
I think I have an
idea about a solution.

00:24:13.650 --> 00:24:15.800
And I was like, I'm a
little bit of a marketer.

00:24:15.800 --> 00:24:17.967
So I'm like, oh, Girls Who
Code, that's a cool name.

00:24:17.967 --> 00:24:19.340
Let me see if it's on GoDaddy.

00:24:19.340 --> 00:24:20.360
It was there.

00:24:20.360 --> 00:24:21.590
I bought it for like $1.99.

00:24:21.590 --> 00:24:23.730
[LAUGHTER]

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:29.210
Sometimes when we have ideas,
we don't tell people about them

00:24:29.210 --> 00:24:31.647
because we think
they're not perfect yet.

00:24:31.647 --> 00:24:32.480
So I didn't do that.

00:24:32.480 --> 00:24:33.590
So when I would meet
people, they'd be like,

00:24:33.590 --> 00:24:34.130
what are you working on?

00:24:34.130 --> 00:24:36.130
I'm like, well, I got
this idea, Girls Who Code.

00:24:36.130 --> 00:24:37.370
And they're like, oh.

00:24:37.370 --> 00:24:40.390
My first funder was
actually Google.

00:24:40.390 --> 00:24:41.250
It was my friend.

00:24:41.250 --> 00:24:41.430
JASON SPERO: I didn't know that.

00:24:41.430 --> 00:24:43.555
RESHMA SAUJANI: I don't
even know if you knew this.

00:24:43.555 --> 00:24:45.710
It was this guy,
Alex [? Abelin, ?]

00:24:45.710 --> 00:24:48.910
who was running community
affairs at Google in New York.

00:24:48.910 --> 00:24:51.590
And he had this budget
where he could actually

00:24:51.590 --> 00:24:57.470
give $10,000, $20,000 to
different organizations.

00:24:57.470 --> 00:24:59.430
So we were at a conference.

00:24:59.430 --> 00:25:00.630
And I was talking to him.

00:25:00.630 --> 00:25:02.210
And he's like, oh,
my god, I love it.

00:25:02.210 --> 00:25:04.685
He actually just
sent me the note.

00:25:04.685 --> 00:25:05.810
And he said, you know what?

00:25:05.810 --> 00:25:08.270
I think I can find
$10,000 for you.

00:25:08.270 --> 00:25:10.490
I'm like, oh, my god, you can?

00:25:10.490 --> 00:25:13.050
And so he invested in me.

00:25:13.050 --> 00:25:14.690
And then I was like,
oh, I got Google.

00:25:14.690 --> 00:25:16.742
So I can do this.

00:25:16.742 --> 00:25:17.700
And then I got Twitter.

00:25:17.700 --> 00:25:20.480
And then all these
little pieces of dollars

00:25:20.480 --> 00:25:25.010
were legitimacy, legitimacy
of this idea that was simply

00:25:25.010 --> 00:25:26.820
just an idea in my head.

00:25:26.820 --> 00:25:30.890
And then I just went too
far that I couldn't quit.

00:25:30.890 --> 00:25:33.890
And I had to just
do one program.

00:25:33.890 --> 00:25:35.345
And here we are.

00:25:35.345 --> 00:25:37.970
JASON SPERO: You have said that
the perfection cycle is getting

00:25:37.970 --> 00:25:38.898
worse .

00:25:38.898 --> 00:25:41.315
Can you talk about the role
of social media in perfection?

00:25:41.315 --> 00:25:42.770
RESHMA SAUJANI: Oh,
my god, like five

00:25:42.770 --> 00:25:45.350
minutes scrolling on Instagram
and your anxiety peaks, right?

00:25:48.200 --> 00:25:49.640
It hasn't helped.

00:25:49.640 --> 00:25:52.190
I mean, most of us
will take 500 selfies

00:25:52.190 --> 00:25:54.020
to take that perfect
selfie, right?

00:25:54.020 --> 00:25:55.160
And you'll take one.

00:25:55.160 --> 00:25:55.970
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:55.970 --> 00:26:00.710
It's like social
media exacerbates

00:26:00.710 --> 00:26:01.980
the perfectionism in me.

00:26:01.980 --> 00:26:05.270
And then we also think
that all these people,

00:26:05.270 --> 00:26:07.052
why am I not happy?

00:26:07.052 --> 00:26:08.510
Look at all these
other people that

00:26:08.510 --> 00:26:09.920
are living these perfect lives.

00:26:09.920 --> 00:26:12.780
And what's wrong with mine?

00:26:12.780 --> 00:26:13.500
AUDIENCE: Hello.

00:26:13.500 --> 00:26:15.080
So outside of Google,
I do a lot of work

00:26:15.080 --> 00:26:16.913
with helping high school
students understand

00:26:16.913 --> 00:26:18.150
what personal development is.

00:26:18.150 --> 00:26:19.640
And so I was just wondering
if you can go back

00:26:19.640 --> 00:26:21.723
to high school, what do
you wish that you invested

00:26:21.723 --> 00:26:23.335
in yourself more?

00:26:23.335 --> 00:26:25.085
RESHMA SAUJANI: Ah,
what a great question.

00:26:28.130 --> 00:26:32.640
I wish that I had learned this
whole brave not perfect thing

00:26:32.640 --> 00:26:33.140
more.

00:26:35.410 --> 00:26:37.160
One of the things I
talk about in the book

00:26:37.160 --> 00:26:40.220
is this idea of doing
something you suck at.

00:26:40.220 --> 00:26:44.420
So every man I know does
something he sucks at--

00:26:44.420 --> 00:26:50.870
golf, tennis,
fantasy, basketball.

00:26:50.870 --> 00:26:52.615
President Obama
sucks at basketball

00:26:52.615 --> 00:26:53.990
and plays it all
the time, right?

00:26:53.990 --> 00:26:57.980
It's like they can do
things that they are not

00:26:57.980 --> 00:27:00.150
good at but they love.

00:27:00.150 --> 00:27:01.640
We don't have that.

00:27:01.640 --> 00:27:04.250
Most of us will not even
go to a Soul Cycle class

00:27:04.250 --> 00:27:06.050
till we're "fit," right?

00:27:06.050 --> 00:27:07.910
The point of going
to an exercise class

00:27:07.910 --> 00:27:10.130
is to get fit, right?

00:27:10.130 --> 00:27:12.920
And so I have
started, at 40, doing

00:27:12.920 --> 00:27:16.040
things that I'm not
good at but that I like.

00:27:16.040 --> 00:27:18.640
I love this Savasana
thing at yoga.

00:27:18.640 --> 00:27:21.050
I can't do a headstand,
barely can do a Child's Pose.

00:27:21.050 --> 00:27:22.550
And I wouldn't go
to yoga because I

00:27:22.550 --> 00:27:24.800
was too embarrassed, right?

00:27:24.800 --> 00:27:27.720
Now I do things that I
like, but I'm not good at.

00:27:27.720 --> 00:27:30.450
I wish I did that
when I was younger.

00:27:30.450 --> 00:27:31.280
I missed out.

00:27:31.280 --> 00:27:37.730
I loved gymnastics, but I
couldn't do a cartwheel.

00:27:37.730 --> 00:27:38.930
And I still remember that.

00:27:38.930 --> 00:27:42.230
I can still feel that feeling
of being in my gymnastics class

00:27:42.230 --> 00:27:45.590
and feeling like a jerk
because I couldn't do anything

00:27:45.590 --> 00:27:48.260
and just wanting to
run out of the room.

00:27:48.260 --> 00:27:51.080
And I wish that I had
just stayed with things

00:27:51.080 --> 00:27:54.410
that I was mediocre at that I
enjoyed and knew what it felt

00:27:54.410 --> 00:27:57.620
like, knew what it feels like
to be Barack Obama playing

00:27:57.620 --> 00:27:59.240
basketball.

00:27:59.240 --> 00:28:00.337
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:28:00.337 --> 00:28:01.670
JASON SPERO: One of the things--

00:28:01.670 --> 00:28:03.570
I want to stay with the
questions from the crowd.

00:28:03.570 --> 00:28:05.570
But one of the things
that struck me is you also

00:28:05.570 --> 00:28:08.510
point out that while it's great
to have a Beyonce or a Venus

00:28:08.510 --> 00:28:10.920
Williams or Serena
Williams or whatever it is,

00:28:10.920 --> 00:28:13.010
that's also an impossible
standard as well.

00:28:13.010 --> 00:28:13.580
RESHMA SAUJANI: Totally.

00:28:13.580 --> 00:28:14.372
JASON SPERO: Right?

00:28:14.372 --> 00:28:16.403
So when you go out
to do the cartwheel,

00:28:16.403 --> 00:28:17.570
you shouldn't be aiming to--

00:28:17.570 --> 00:28:19.903
RESHMA SAUJANI: No, you should
be aiming to be mediocre.

00:28:19.903 --> 00:28:21.630
You should be just aiming to--

00:28:21.630 --> 00:28:24.005
we need more feeling like what
it's like to be mediocre--

00:28:24.005 --> 00:28:25.922
JASON SPERO: The story
of my life, by the way.

00:28:25.922 --> 00:28:28.580
RESHMA SAUJANI: --not what it's
like to feel excellent, I mean,

00:28:28.580 --> 00:28:30.500
not excellent, but like A plus.

00:28:30.500 --> 00:28:32.980
AUDIENCE: But they also
started not being good, right?

00:28:32.980 --> 00:28:33.280
RESHMA SAUJANI: Yeah.

00:28:33.280 --> 00:28:35.290
AUDIENCE: Like Serena
Williams probably sucked.

00:28:35.290 --> 00:28:35.540
RESHMA SAUJANI: Yeah.

00:28:35.540 --> 00:28:37.790
JASON SPERO: I'm going to
repeat just because somebody

00:28:37.790 --> 00:28:38.660
is watching on video.

00:28:38.660 --> 00:28:40.700
She said, all the people
that you could name that

00:28:40.700 --> 00:28:42.075
are exceptional,
I think, and you

00:28:42.075 --> 00:28:43.867
said Serena Williams
started being mediocre

00:28:43.867 --> 00:28:46.033
and built their way up
through work and all of that.

00:28:46.033 --> 00:28:48.590
RESHMA SAUJANI: It's that
idea of 10,000 hours, right?

00:28:48.590 --> 00:28:50.660
If you put enough
time into something,

00:28:50.660 --> 00:28:55.080
you can do it "well."

00:28:55.080 --> 00:28:55.998
JASON SPERO: Please.

00:28:55.998 --> 00:28:56.540
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:28:56.540 --> 00:28:57.850
My name is Ishra.

00:28:57.850 --> 00:28:59.990
I am very fortunate to
be a middle school club

00:28:59.990 --> 00:29:02.960
facilitator and the
club's success specialist

00:29:02.960 --> 00:29:03.903
for the organization.

00:29:03.903 --> 00:29:04.820
RESHMA SAUJANI: Great.

00:29:04.820 --> 00:29:05.570
Thank you so much.

00:29:05.570 --> 00:29:08.150
AUDIENCE: Thank you for all
that Girls Who Code does

00:29:08.150 --> 00:29:10.290
and thank you for today's talk.

00:29:10.290 --> 00:29:14.150
My question for you is,
can you share your vision

00:29:14.150 --> 00:29:16.830
for the clubs for
the next five years?

00:29:16.830 --> 00:29:19.060
RESHMA SAUJANI: Yeah, world
domination, basically.

00:29:19.060 --> 00:29:22.040
[LAUGHTER]

00:29:22.850 --> 00:29:25.457
One of the things
that frustrates me--

00:29:25.457 --> 00:29:27.290
and we have a report
coming out about this--

00:29:27.290 --> 00:29:30.830
is that it's sometimes
said that things

00:29:30.830 --> 00:29:32.070
are going great in school.

00:29:32.070 --> 00:29:33.830
And that's just not true.

00:29:33.830 --> 00:29:35.283
You walk into any
computer science

00:29:35.283 --> 00:29:36.950
classroom in the
country, and it's still

00:29:36.950 --> 00:29:39.500
80% boys and 20% girls.

00:29:39.500 --> 00:29:42.140
And so we use the
clubs as a vehicle

00:29:42.140 --> 00:29:45.900
to get girls interested so
that they will then go sign up.

00:29:45.900 --> 00:29:49.370
So when you look at the APCS
numbers going up, that's us.

00:29:49.370 --> 00:29:50.760
That's us, right?

00:29:50.760 --> 00:29:53.150
And I will take credit for it.

00:29:53.150 --> 00:29:54.380
Because it's us.

00:29:54.380 --> 00:29:56.750
And a lot of it is
because of the clubs.

00:29:56.750 --> 00:29:59.450
Because what happens is that
girls get exposed to it,

00:29:59.450 --> 00:30:02.780
and they're like, oh, this
is fun making a robot dance

00:30:02.780 --> 00:30:04.150
and building this.

00:30:04.150 --> 00:30:05.400
It's not as hard as I thought.

00:30:05.400 --> 00:30:07.192
And they bring their
friends, and then they

00:30:07.192 --> 00:30:10.370
go sign up for CS class or APCS.

00:30:10.370 --> 00:30:13.790
And so I would just like to
grow and grow and grow and grow

00:30:13.790 --> 00:30:14.835
and grow.

00:30:14.835 --> 00:30:16.460
The other thing that
I've been thinking

00:30:16.460 --> 00:30:19.790
a lot about is that my
goal this year-- we're

00:30:19.790 --> 00:30:22.130
launching international-- is
to start teaching Girls Who

00:30:22.130 --> 00:30:24.410
Code clubs at refugee camps.

00:30:24.410 --> 00:30:26.460
Because we forget that
half of the country,

00:30:26.460 --> 00:30:28.370
they don't have computers.

00:30:28.370 --> 00:30:30.657
And that as automation is
changing everything about

00:30:30.657 --> 00:30:32.990
the way that we live and work,
we cannot leave half this

00:30:32.990 --> 00:30:34.460
country behind.

00:30:34.460 --> 00:30:38.240
One of the reasons why
we have so much division

00:30:38.240 --> 00:30:39.710
is because far
too many Americans

00:30:39.710 --> 00:30:41.120
feel like their
kids are actually

00:30:41.120 --> 00:30:43.910
not going to have the same
chance that they've had.

00:30:43.910 --> 00:30:45.740
And if we don't
get them exposure

00:30:45.740 --> 00:30:48.710
to computational
thinking and computer

00:30:48.710 --> 00:30:51.043
science as early
as we possibly can,

00:30:51.043 --> 00:30:52.460
they are going to
get left behind.

00:30:52.460 --> 00:30:55.430
And we're going to actually have
more division in our country.

00:30:55.430 --> 00:30:57.890
So we always like to start
with our clubs, what's

00:30:57.890 --> 00:30:59.270
the hardest to reach places?

00:30:59.270 --> 00:31:02.670
Where's the poorest
places in our country?

00:31:02.670 --> 00:31:04.760
I want to go there.

00:31:04.760 --> 00:31:06.580
AUDIENCE: OK, thank you so much.

00:31:06.580 --> 00:31:07.773
JASON SPERO: Thank you.

00:31:07.773 --> 00:31:10.190
AUDIENCE: Yeah, so I just
wanted to hear a little bit more

00:31:10.190 --> 00:31:13.520
from you about when you talked
on throwing away the existing

00:31:13.520 --> 00:31:15.520
parenting books and how
I can shift my mindset--

00:31:15.520 --> 00:31:17.437
RESHMA SAUJANI: Yeah,
so much pressure, right?

00:31:17.437 --> 00:31:20.840
AUDIENCE: --in raising her
to be different than maybe

00:31:20.840 --> 00:31:22.050
what I was raised as.

00:31:22.050 --> 00:31:22.940
RESHMA SAUJANI:
Yeah, look, I think

00:31:22.940 --> 00:31:24.898
that one of the things
that we have to remember

00:31:24.898 --> 00:31:26.900
is that we're not with
them all the time.

00:31:26.900 --> 00:31:28.400
And there's so many
different people

00:31:28.400 --> 00:31:32.480
that they're exposed to
that immediately, culture

00:31:32.480 --> 00:31:35.180
plays a huge role in how
we think boys should behave

00:31:35.180 --> 00:31:37.230
and how we think
girls should behave.

00:31:37.230 --> 00:31:41.330
So I think the important thing
early on is to let them--

00:31:41.330 --> 00:31:44.060
it sounds simple, but
let her get dirty.

00:31:44.060 --> 00:31:46.070
Stop every bone
in your body when

00:31:46.070 --> 00:31:50.450
you see a booger in her
nose to go get a napkin

00:31:50.450 --> 00:31:52.940
or when her hair
looks like a mess.

00:31:52.940 --> 00:31:56.430
And the thing is, we think
it's a reflection of us.

00:31:56.430 --> 00:31:58.090
But it's not.

00:31:58.090 --> 00:31:59.798
My son looks like a
pig pen all the time,

00:31:59.798 --> 00:32:02.007
and I don't think it's a
reflection of me-- at least,

00:32:02.007 --> 00:32:02.810
I tell myself that.

00:32:02.810 --> 00:32:04.932
[LAUGHTER]

00:32:04.932 --> 00:32:08.690
So let her get physically
messy and also let

00:32:08.690 --> 00:32:11.900
her get physically hurt.

00:32:11.900 --> 00:32:14.840
You want to see her with
tons of scabs on her knees.

00:32:14.840 --> 00:32:16.280
And for her to not--

00:32:16.280 --> 00:32:17.387
for you to not--

00:32:17.387 --> 00:32:18.470
because I feel like it's--

00:32:18.470 --> 00:32:20.095
I was hanging out a
friend this weekend

00:32:20.095 --> 00:32:22.811
who has a twin boy and girl.

00:32:22.811 --> 00:32:25.100
And the girl hurt her--

00:32:25.100 --> 00:32:27.320
her daughter, Jade, is
actually quite bigger

00:32:27.320 --> 00:32:28.940
than her son, Tusk.

00:32:28.940 --> 00:32:30.230
And we're both reading a book.

00:32:30.230 --> 00:32:32.870
And they're both
fighting, play fighting.

00:32:32.870 --> 00:32:35.160
And she immediately was
like, Tusky, be careful.

00:32:35.160 --> 00:32:36.550
Don't knock your sister over.

00:32:36.550 --> 00:32:37.747
I was like, his sister?

00:32:37.747 --> 00:32:39.830
She's knocking him over,
and she's twice his size.

00:32:39.830 --> 00:32:40.997
But you see what I'm saying.

00:32:40.997 --> 00:32:44.600
It is our instinct to go
towards physical protection

00:32:44.600 --> 00:32:45.470
of our girls.

00:32:45.470 --> 00:32:47.533
Try not to do that.

00:32:47.533 --> 00:32:48.950
JASON SPERO: I
would add something

00:32:48.950 --> 00:32:51.432
you and I have talked
about is, maybe not at two,

00:32:51.432 --> 00:32:53.640
but make them aware of how
much the world around them

00:32:53.640 --> 00:32:55.242
is going to send
them signals as well.

00:32:55.242 --> 00:32:56.950
They're going to get
it from their media.

00:32:56.950 --> 00:32:58.700
They're going get it,
in my family's case,

00:32:58.700 --> 00:33:00.200
from their third
grade math teacher.

00:33:00.200 --> 00:33:01.825
They're going to get
it from everywhere

00:33:01.825 --> 00:33:02.830
that you can't control.

00:33:02.830 --> 00:33:05.540
But if can recognize it,
it's so powerful thing

00:33:05.540 --> 00:33:07.253
maybe to call it out
that someone else is

00:33:07.253 --> 00:33:08.420
trying to put them in a box.

00:33:08.420 --> 00:33:10.300
RESHMA SAUJANI: Yep.

00:33:10.300 --> 00:33:12.880
AUDIENCE: Hi, my
name is [INAUDIBLE]..

00:33:12.880 --> 00:33:17.990
I've been pretty fortunate where
I've had advantages in life.

00:33:17.990 --> 00:33:21.580
And one of the challenges that
I face now is that, at times,

00:33:21.580 --> 00:33:24.490
the men around me
get very insecure.

00:33:24.490 --> 00:33:31.120
And so have you thought
about maybe cultivating

00:33:31.120 --> 00:33:37.240
that security in boys growing
up so that they don't feel

00:33:37.240 --> 00:33:39.310
like they always have
to be the manly man

00:33:39.310 --> 00:33:42.340
and be the sole provider
and stuff like that?

00:33:42.340 --> 00:33:44.920
RESHMA SAUJANI: They feel
insecure because why?

00:33:44.920 --> 00:33:47.770
Because your talent,
your ability,

00:33:47.770 --> 00:33:51.220
or because they feel
like-- what do you mean?

00:33:51.220 --> 00:33:53.560
AUDIENCE: So at times,
I've encountered

00:33:53.560 --> 00:33:57.640
men who can't cope with
having a female manager.

00:33:57.640 --> 00:33:59.920
RESHMA SAUJANI: So I
feel like that is about--

00:33:59.920 --> 00:34:01.540
so those are two
different things.

00:34:01.540 --> 00:34:03.910
So I think that, when
I think about this,

00:34:03.910 --> 00:34:07.450
so I want my son, who is very
like a little mini Gandhi

00:34:07.450 --> 00:34:10.540
to feel like he
can be vulnerable.

00:34:10.540 --> 00:34:11.409
And he's sweet.

00:34:11.409 --> 00:34:14.550
And he's not that tough
rumble guy, right?

00:34:14.550 --> 00:34:17.050
And I don't want people to keep
trying to tell him that he's

00:34:17.050 --> 00:34:18.550
got to be somebody else.

00:34:18.550 --> 00:34:20.860
I do pray on a daily
basis that he does not

00:34:20.860 --> 00:34:21.854
become Brett Kavanaugh.

00:34:21.854 --> 00:34:23.979
And that is the thing that
I think is an obligation

00:34:23.979 --> 00:34:26.159
as a-- right--

00:34:26.159 --> 00:34:28.030
is like I got to make sure.

00:34:28.030 --> 00:34:30.400
And so he has constantly
surrounded by women.

00:34:30.400 --> 00:34:32.870
But the second thing you're
talking about is, I think,

00:34:32.870 --> 00:34:34.550
very important.

00:34:34.550 --> 00:34:38.320
Which is this conversation
about women in tech,

00:34:38.320 --> 00:34:40.750
it's ultimately about power.

00:34:40.750 --> 00:34:44.690
We are talking about a
distribution of power.

00:34:44.690 --> 00:34:46.449
And we have to be
honest about the fact

00:34:46.449 --> 00:34:50.199
that that is not going to
make men feel comfortable.

00:34:50.199 --> 00:34:52.270
And also we have
been raised to always

00:34:52.270 --> 00:34:59.020
think about prioritizing
men's feelings, right?

00:34:59.020 --> 00:35:02.650
And because we've been raised
to be toxic people pleasers,

00:35:02.650 --> 00:35:04.210
we have to unlearn that.

00:35:04.210 --> 00:35:06.790
So one, we have to stop
caring what they think

00:35:06.790 --> 00:35:07.870
and how they feel--

00:35:07.870 --> 00:35:10.190
period, full stop, done.

00:35:10.190 --> 00:35:12.400
Doesn't matter, right?

00:35:12.400 --> 00:35:15.070
And that is a constant thing.

00:35:15.070 --> 00:35:17.200
Because we want to be liked.

00:35:17.200 --> 00:35:18.700
And then the second
thing is I think

00:35:18.700 --> 00:35:20.190
we have to have a real honest
conversation about power,

00:35:20.190 --> 00:35:21.857
and we have to activate
our male allies.

00:35:21.857 --> 00:35:23.950
One of the best things
that happened last year

00:35:23.950 --> 00:35:25.630
was that I was speaking
at the Rochester

00:35:25.630 --> 00:35:27.440
Institute of Technology.

00:35:27.440 --> 00:35:33.400
RIT had gone from 13%
female to 33% female.

00:35:33.400 --> 00:35:35.740
And so I'm speaking at the
Women in Computing group.

00:35:35.740 --> 00:35:39.230
And there's these three dudes
that are sitting in the back.

00:35:39.230 --> 00:35:40.638
And I'm like, who are you?

00:35:40.638 --> 00:35:42.430
And they're like, we're
the men who support

00:35:42.430 --> 00:35:44.140
the Women in Computing group.

00:35:44.140 --> 00:35:45.325
They had formed a club.

00:35:45.325 --> 00:35:46.450
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:46.450 --> 00:35:49.360
They had literally
formed a club.

00:35:49.360 --> 00:35:51.760
And it was amazing.

00:35:51.760 --> 00:35:57.933
And their job was to help
support women to be more brave

00:35:57.933 --> 00:35:59.600
or when were
microaggressions were made,

00:35:59.600 --> 00:36:01.240
they would say something.

00:36:01.240 --> 00:36:05.398
Or sometimes their job
was to just shut up.

00:36:05.398 --> 00:36:07.690
You talk about this in our
boardroom oftentimes, right?

00:36:07.690 --> 00:36:11.240
It's like men talk 70%
of the time in meetings.

00:36:11.240 --> 00:36:14.560
We can't be brave if
they keep talking, right?

00:36:14.560 --> 00:36:16.960
So part of it, though,
is being able to have

00:36:16.960 --> 00:36:20.590
an honest conversation
with men about this.

00:36:20.590 --> 00:36:24.790
So when your leadership
has been questioned,

00:36:24.790 --> 00:36:28.240
as I'm sure it has been,
you probably go home,

00:36:28.240 --> 00:36:31.260
and you're just mad.

00:36:31.260 --> 00:36:33.360
I need you to confront.

00:36:33.360 --> 00:36:34.520
I need you to confront.

00:36:34.520 --> 00:36:37.290
And I need us to have the honest
conversations that we simply

00:36:37.290 --> 00:36:40.350
need to have with men, and we
have to come from the place

00:36:40.350 --> 00:36:42.578
that I think that they
want to do better.

00:36:42.578 --> 00:36:44.120
And I'm going to
keep believing that.

00:36:44.120 --> 00:36:47.120
I'm going to keep believing that
they are my Rochester Institute

00:36:47.120 --> 00:36:50.040
club and that they
want to do better.

00:36:50.040 --> 00:36:52.970
And even though post-MeToo
courage has been contagious

00:36:52.970 --> 00:36:57.020
for women, we can't assume that
it's been contagious for men.

00:36:57.020 --> 00:36:59.870
We can't assume that they know
what to say and what to do

00:36:59.870 --> 00:37:02.960
and that they're often not
coming from an authentic place,

00:37:02.960 --> 00:37:05.300
which is being able to say
whatever they want to say,

00:37:05.300 --> 00:37:08.900
because no one has told
them that they can't.

00:37:08.900 --> 00:37:12.200
And so I think it's
an opportunity for us.

00:37:12.200 --> 00:37:13.880
AUDIENCE: My question
is not perfect.

00:37:13.880 --> 00:37:14.590
RESHMA SAUJANI: I love it.

00:37:14.590 --> 00:37:15.548
AUDIENCE: But I'll try.

00:37:15.548 --> 00:37:19.700
So I want to hear a little bit
about fighting the existing

00:37:19.700 --> 00:37:21.200
structure.

00:37:21.200 --> 00:37:23.920
As you said, it's really hard.

00:37:23.920 --> 00:37:27.080
Existing companies have
been built without us.

00:37:27.080 --> 00:37:31.130
So even like we are at Google.

00:37:31.130 --> 00:37:33.690
It's supposed to be
the better ones, right?

00:37:33.690 --> 00:37:35.350
But when you look
at the leadership

00:37:35.350 --> 00:37:38.030
and when you're sitting in the
meeting room, a lot of times,

00:37:38.030 --> 00:37:40.670
it's majority male still.

00:37:40.670 --> 00:37:44.060
And I think that
women, they experience

00:37:44.060 --> 00:37:47.060
explicit, implicit
[INAUDIBLE] as well as

00:37:47.060 --> 00:37:49.830
just the self-doubt as well.

00:37:49.830 --> 00:37:53.450
So even at Google,
I've seen women

00:37:53.450 --> 00:37:55.430
leaving the workforce
because of this,

00:37:55.430 --> 00:37:59.570
or they change teams that
are supposedly better,

00:37:59.570 --> 00:38:03.110
or they leave to
another company.

00:38:03.110 --> 00:38:06.680
Or they just stay
to fight, right?

00:38:06.680 --> 00:38:10.260
So what should we-- what
is, in your opinion,

00:38:10.260 --> 00:38:13.520
what is the best kind
of survival defense

00:38:13.520 --> 00:38:18.080
mechanism for us in
the existing structure?

00:38:18.080 --> 00:38:19.810
And also, at what expense?

00:38:19.810 --> 00:38:23.142
So in order for us to
stay here and fight, not

00:38:23.142 --> 00:38:24.350
like at Google specifically--

00:38:24.350 --> 00:38:26.060
RESHMA SAUJANI:
It can be Google.

00:38:26.060 --> 00:38:28.370
AUDIENCE: Yeah,
stay here and fight,

00:38:28.370 --> 00:38:33.720
but also we need to think about
our mental health as well.

00:38:33.720 --> 00:38:35.590
So yeah, what is
the right balance?

00:38:35.590 --> 00:38:39.030
RESHMA SAUJANI: So first of
all, I think we have to--

00:38:39.030 --> 00:38:41.280
Google's not perfect.

00:38:41.280 --> 00:38:42.910
Google's not perfect.

00:38:42.910 --> 00:38:44.220
No company is.

00:38:44.220 --> 00:38:45.720
Google may be
trying really hard,

00:38:45.720 --> 00:38:47.342
and that's awesome, right?

00:38:47.342 --> 00:38:48.550
But we still have work to do.

00:38:48.550 --> 00:38:50.050
And I think we got
to get to a place

00:38:50.050 --> 00:38:52.170
where we can stay and
fight and also acknowledge

00:38:52.170 --> 00:38:55.920
the change that needs to happen
and that be OK and not feel

00:38:55.920 --> 00:39:00.540
threatened by that or not
feel your personal success

00:39:00.540 --> 00:39:04.350
is going to be compromised
if you speak truth to power.

00:39:04.350 --> 00:39:07.950
And so that's why, to
me, this book is about,

00:39:07.950 --> 00:39:11.100
how do we build our
everyday courage?

00:39:11.100 --> 00:39:13.020
You're seeing six women
running for president,

00:39:13.020 --> 00:39:16.140
all these men basically
taken down by MeToo.

00:39:16.140 --> 00:39:20.410
But still, things happen
to us on a daily basis

00:39:20.410 --> 00:39:23.847
that diminish our courage.

00:39:23.847 --> 00:39:25.680
And so we can't speak
out at the big moments

00:39:25.680 --> 00:39:27.430
because we don't even
know how to stand up

00:39:27.430 --> 00:39:28.920
for ourselves anymore.

00:39:28.920 --> 00:39:30.420
So we have to start
working on that,

00:39:30.420 --> 00:39:32.970
because we have
to stay and fight.

00:39:32.970 --> 00:39:36.300
So I think the first thing
is, how do we practice

00:39:36.300 --> 00:39:38.370
building our bravery muscle?

00:39:38.370 --> 00:39:41.950
How does every time a
microaggression or something

00:39:41.950 --> 00:39:45.870
is said in my workplace or
at home or on the street, I

00:39:45.870 --> 00:39:48.240
actually speak up for myself?

00:39:48.240 --> 00:39:50.850
And we get into the
practice of doing that.

00:39:50.850 --> 00:39:53.610
I think the second thing is
is we can only stay and fight

00:39:53.610 --> 00:39:56.050
if we have sisterhood
with each other.

00:39:56.050 --> 00:39:57.750
How do we support each other?

00:39:57.750 --> 00:39:59.760
Every single one of
you that's a manager

00:39:59.760 --> 00:40:02.010
should be promoting
someone who is a woman.

00:40:02.010 --> 00:40:03.480
You should, period.

00:40:03.480 --> 00:40:07.030
And you shouldn't
feel bad about that.

00:40:07.030 --> 00:40:09.190
Because the only way we
change the power structures

00:40:09.190 --> 00:40:11.557
is if we lift each other up.

00:40:11.557 --> 00:40:13.390
You can't have someone
open the door for you

00:40:13.390 --> 00:40:15.970
and then you kick
it on the way in.

00:40:15.970 --> 00:40:17.740
And so part of it
is understanding

00:40:17.740 --> 00:40:20.600
why do we not have
sisterhood with each other.

00:40:20.600 --> 00:40:23.140
And I think a lot of that
has to come from the fact

00:40:23.140 --> 00:40:27.730
that so many of us have
things that we wanted to do,

00:40:27.730 --> 00:40:29.770
whether it was start
a company, go here,

00:40:29.770 --> 00:40:31.930
maybe not have a
baby, whatever it is.

00:40:31.930 --> 00:40:33.670
And you talked
yourself out of it.

00:40:33.670 --> 00:40:35.830
Or someone else
talked you out of it.

00:40:35.830 --> 00:40:39.310
And then you see someone
else doing the very thing

00:40:39.310 --> 00:40:41.630
that you wanted to do.

00:40:41.630 --> 00:40:46.140
And you're left with
regret and envy.

00:40:46.140 --> 00:40:47.980
So we have to go
to that place where

00:40:47.980 --> 00:40:50.940
our envy is and acknowledge
our deepest dreams.

00:40:50.940 --> 00:40:53.250
And then we can
lift each other up.

00:40:53.250 --> 00:40:55.530
The third thing is
is I really think

00:40:55.530 --> 00:40:58.410
that we have to start having
these honest conversations

00:40:58.410 --> 00:41:01.140
with our male allies.

00:41:01.140 --> 00:41:02.490
So many men I know--

00:41:02.490 --> 00:41:05.085
again, I've been in a room
where a rape joke was made

00:41:05.085 --> 00:41:06.960
or something was said
that was inappropriate.

00:41:06.960 --> 00:41:08.940
And maybe they laughed
or didn't say anything.

00:41:08.940 --> 00:41:10.690
And then they went
home, and they're like,

00:41:10.690 --> 00:41:13.650
I can't believe that was said.

00:41:13.650 --> 00:41:16.020
They have to be brave too.

00:41:16.020 --> 00:41:18.000
It can't just be on us.

00:41:18.000 --> 00:41:21.210
It can't just be on
us to change things.

00:41:21.210 --> 00:41:26.330
But if we want to make things
different, you've got to fight.

00:41:26.330 --> 00:41:27.120
And guess what?

00:41:27.120 --> 00:41:29.060
It doesn't always feel good.

00:41:29.060 --> 00:41:30.462
It doesn't always feel good.

00:41:30.462 --> 00:41:32.420
But it has to happen,
because it's the only way

00:41:32.420 --> 00:41:34.447
that-- nothing will change.

00:41:34.447 --> 00:41:35.280
Nothing will change.

00:41:35.280 --> 00:41:39.830
And I say that as
someone who is a lawyer.

00:41:39.830 --> 00:41:42.590
My law school class
was 50-50% women.

00:41:42.590 --> 00:41:44.930
30 years later or
20 years later,

00:41:44.930 --> 00:41:46.730
I can go to any law
firm in this country,

00:41:46.730 --> 00:41:49.430
and it's still 80%
men and 20% women.

00:41:49.430 --> 00:41:51.680
Nothing's changed, because
people don't give up power.

00:41:51.680 --> 00:41:54.170
You have to take it.

00:41:54.170 --> 00:41:56.600
And you have to ask yourself,
are you ready and willing

00:41:56.600 --> 00:41:58.748
to take it?

00:41:58.748 --> 00:42:01.206
JASON SPERO: Oh, hello, on the
livestream, what do you got?

00:42:01.206 --> 00:42:02.720
AUDIENCE: Oh, hi.

00:42:02.720 --> 00:42:06.415
I actually think that the last
couple offered some feedback.

00:42:06.415 --> 00:42:08.040
JASON SPERO: Yeah,
we're getting it to.

00:42:08.040 --> 00:42:08.790
But fight through.

00:42:08.790 --> 00:42:11.055
[LAUGHTER]

00:42:11.055 --> 00:42:15.900
AUDIENCE: OK, well,
it's imperfect, yes.

00:42:15.900 --> 00:42:17.250
I've been fighting a long time.

00:42:17.250 --> 00:42:20.820
And it actually is
really, really hard

00:42:20.820 --> 00:42:23.850
to build alliances with other
women for exactly the things

00:42:23.850 --> 00:42:25.320
that you just mentioned.

00:42:25.320 --> 00:42:31.950
I see the envy of most
of my best managers

00:42:31.950 --> 00:42:33.520
with the exception
of two people.

00:42:33.520 --> 00:42:35.940
And I've been a long-term
contractor in Silicon Valley.

00:42:35.940 --> 00:42:39.480
Most of my best
managers have been men.

00:42:39.480 --> 00:42:44.820
OK, so I think that's
really unfortunate.

00:42:44.820 --> 00:42:46.830
And I'm of an older generation.

00:42:46.830 --> 00:42:48.570
I wasn't in the
coddled generation.

00:42:48.570 --> 00:42:51.480
And my son was not coddled
because I was a single mother.

00:42:51.480 --> 00:42:53.020
So all the things about--

00:42:53.020 --> 00:42:54.800
and also, I was a
[INAUDIBLE] kid.

00:42:54.800 --> 00:42:57.275
And my mother was
[INAUDIBLE] family.

00:42:57.275 --> 00:43:02.240
And I grew up with knees
that have scabs on them

00:43:02.240 --> 00:43:03.510
and all of those things.

00:43:03.510 --> 00:43:06.060
And so I've been
extremely brave.

00:43:06.060 --> 00:43:08.880
And I just have to say
I really want support

00:43:08.880 --> 00:43:12.750
from more women,
women in technology.

00:43:12.750 --> 00:43:16.210
I still have a whole lot to do.

00:43:16.210 --> 00:43:19.800
And I think that what
it is I have a whole lot

00:43:19.800 --> 00:43:21.370
to offer as a mentor.

00:43:21.370 --> 00:43:24.840
But also I need support
from my younger sisters.

00:43:24.840 --> 00:43:26.790
RESHMA SAUJANI: Yeah,
that's so powerful.

00:43:26.790 --> 00:43:27.990
You know what?

00:43:27.990 --> 00:43:30.420
We just got to keep
working on it, right?

00:43:30.420 --> 00:43:31.740
Because so much of this--

00:43:31.740 --> 00:43:33.690
I think about my mother.

00:43:33.690 --> 00:43:36.720
My mother was always
like, you're too fat.

00:43:36.720 --> 00:43:37.470
Stand up straight.

00:43:37.470 --> 00:43:39.262
Really, you're going
to apply for that job?

00:43:39.262 --> 00:43:40.800
You're not going to get that.

00:43:40.800 --> 00:43:43.320
Whereas my father was
like, you can be anything.

00:43:43.320 --> 00:43:44.700
You can be everything.

00:43:44.700 --> 00:43:47.670
And most of us have
mothers like this.

00:43:47.670 --> 00:43:51.330
And it's often because it's
that same perfectionism passed

00:43:51.330 --> 00:43:52.260
over and over.

00:43:52.260 --> 00:43:54.420
Same dreams deferred, right?

00:43:54.420 --> 00:43:57.120
They didn't do the things
that they wanted to do.

00:43:57.120 --> 00:43:58.860
They were constantly criticized.

00:43:58.860 --> 00:44:01.920
And then we pass it on, and we
pass it on, and we pass it on.

00:44:01.920 --> 00:44:03.930
Whereas, oftentimes,
our fathers were

00:44:03.930 --> 00:44:08.440
allowed to be brave and
have flaws and thrive.

00:44:08.440 --> 00:44:10.800
And so they encouraged
us to do the same.

00:44:10.800 --> 00:44:12.780
So we got to break the cycle.

00:44:12.780 --> 00:44:14.800
We got to break the cycle.

00:44:14.800 --> 00:44:18.810
And I think once you
start acknowledging it,

00:44:18.810 --> 00:44:19.900
it can change.

00:44:19.900 --> 00:44:20.650
I always say this.

00:44:20.650 --> 00:44:24.560
I ran for office twice,
and I lost twice.

00:44:24.560 --> 00:44:27.120
But I can celebrate
with my whole heart.

00:44:27.120 --> 00:44:29.080
AOC and I took the stage
last Friday together.

00:44:29.080 --> 00:44:34.380
And it was like, it was felt
so much joy in watching her,

00:44:34.380 --> 00:44:37.410
because at least I tried.

00:44:37.410 --> 00:44:39.420
Whereas if I had
never tried before,

00:44:39.420 --> 00:44:42.450
I would not be able
to even watch CNN.

00:44:42.450 --> 00:44:44.440
It would hurt too much.

00:44:44.440 --> 00:44:47.040
So I think if everybody in
this room goes to the place

00:44:47.040 --> 00:44:50.040
for your envy is,
where your regret is,

00:44:50.040 --> 00:44:53.190
and whatever that is, you
start working on that.

00:44:53.190 --> 00:44:56.280
Even if you take one
step, I think your heart

00:44:56.280 --> 00:44:57.990
will open up to other women.

00:44:57.990 --> 00:44:59.460
I really believe that.

00:44:59.460 --> 00:45:02.850
You will become more
generous, because you can.

00:45:02.850 --> 00:45:05.583
Because there's nothing there
that you're not trying to do.

00:45:05.583 --> 00:45:07.000
JASON SPERO: Just
before you go, I

00:45:07.000 --> 00:45:08.375
want to tell the
person who asked

00:45:08.375 --> 00:45:10.188
the question on the
livestream thank you.

00:45:10.188 --> 00:45:11.230
And also that there was--

00:45:11.230 --> 00:45:11.820
you can't see them.

00:45:11.820 --> 00:45:12.360
They're not on cameras.

00:45:12.360 --> 00:45:13.245
There was a lot of
nodding in the room--

00:45:13.245 --> 00:45:14.320
RESHMA SAUJANI: Yeah,
thank you for that truth--

00:45:14.320 --> 00:45:15.350
JASON SPERO: --when you
asked that question.

00:45:15.350 --> 00:45:17.178
RESHMA SAUJANI:
--because that's so real.

00:45:17.178 --> 00:45:18.720
AUDIENCE: How do
you discern between,

00:45:18.720 --> 00:45:22.140
"I am not enjoying this
because I'm not perfect at it,"

00:45:22.140 --> 00:45:23.700
and "I am not enjoying it?"

00:45:23.700 --> 00:45:25.257
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:25.257 --> 00:45:27.590
RESHMA SAUJANI: I think you
got to do it a couple times.

00:45:27.590 --> 00:45:29.350
You got to do it
a couple of times

00:45:29.350 --> 00:45:33.420
to start getting rid of that
thing of like-- because we tell

00:45:33.420 --> 00:45:36.300
ourselves I'm not enjoying
this because I don't like it.

00:45:36.300 --> 00:45:38.147
But really, it's because
I'm not good at it.

00:45:38.147 --> 00:45:40.230
AUDIENCE: So how do you
think about the threshold,

00:45:40.230 --> 00:45:41.405
just like a few times?

00:45:41.405 --> 00:45:42.780
Or I went through
a coding class,

00:45:42.780 --> 00:45:44.030
and I passed it, gosh darn it.

00:45:44.030 --> 00:45:45.165
But I still hate coding.

00:45:45.165 --> 00:45:46.632
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:46.632 --> 00:45:48.840
RESHMA SAUJANI: But did you
have joy from completion?

00:45:48.840 --> 00:45:49.260
AUDIENCE: No.

00:45:49.260 --> 00:45:49.840
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:49.840 --> 00:45:52.830
I just thought, holy
cow, I'm so glad

00:45:52.830 --> 00:45:55.170
I never have to take
this class again.

00:45:55.170 --> 00:45:56.472
And I never want to be a coder.

00:45:56.472 --> 00:45:57.930
I want to work in
tech, but I'm not

00:45:57.930 --> 00:45:59.050
going to sit in front
of a computer all day.

00:45:59.050 --> 00:45:59.162
RESHMA SAUJANI: Fair.

00:45:59.162 --> 00:46:00.450
Then you passed the test.

00:46:00.450 --> 00:46:01.200
Then you passed the test.

00:46:01.200 --> 00:46:02.330
It has nothing to do with--

00:46:02.330 --> 00:46:04.830
AUDIENCE: It took a long time,
but I think I knew beforehand

00:46:04.830 --> 00:46:05.080
that I wasn't in to it.

00:46:05.080 --> 00:46:06.622
RESHMA SAUJANI:
Well, so I would say.

00:46:06.622 --> 00:46:09.630
In this book, I say it's
like the drama wisdom test.

00:46:09.630 --> 00:46:10.608
That's why I call it.

00:46:10.608 --> 00:46:12.900
OK, so is this your drama
talking where you're saying I

00:46:12.900 --> 00:46:15.000
don't like something because you
really just are not good at it?

00:46:15.000 --> 00:46:16.530
But it's your
wisdom, which you've

00:46:16.530 --> 00:46:20.040
gained from actually trying
it and given it yourself.

00:46:20.040 --> 00:46:21.882
And you were like,
I don't like this.

00:46:21.882 --> 00:46:22.840
AUDIENCE: Cool, thanks.

00:46:22.840 --> 00:46:24.632
RESHMA SAUJANI: It's
how I feel about golf.

00:46:24.632 --> 00:46:26.260
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:26.260 --> 00:46:29.688
JASON SPERO: It's also how I
feel about golf, by the way.

00:46:29.688 --> 00:46:30.230
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:46:30.230 --> 00:46:31.855
So first, I just want
to say I'm really

00:46:31.855 --> 00:46:33.680
grateful that we got
to come here and meet

00:46:33.680 --> 00:46:35.700
you and everything.

00:46:35.700 --> 00:46:37.610
And my question is,
so basically, I'm

00:46:37.610 --> 00:46:39.280
one of the founders
for the Girls

00:46:39.280 --> 00:46:40.910
Who Code club at our school.

00:46:40.910 --> 00:46:42.800
And we have a process
where we basically

00:46:42.800 --> 00:46:45.710
have to present in front
of the student council.

00:46:45.710 --> 00:46:47.630
And they pass our club.

00:46:47.630 --> 00:46:50.822
So we actually had
to go three times.

00:46:50.822 --> 00:46:52.280
And the third time
is when our club

00:46:52.280 --> 00:46:54.470
got passed, which
seems like not a lot,

00:46:54.470 --> 00:46:55.595
but that's really uncommon.

00:46:55.595 --> 00:46:56.540
RESHMA SAUJANI:
No, that's crazy.

00:46:56.540 --> 00:46:58.790
AUDIENCE: People usually get
passed in the first time,

00:46:58.790 --> 00:47:00.530
or they just don't.

00:47:00.530 --> 00:47:01.670
But yeah, we kept going.

00:47:01.670 --> 00:47:05.882
But a lot of the criticism we
faced was by girls in the room.

00:47:05.882 --> 00:47:07.340
When they asked
us, they were like,

00:47:07.340 --> 00:47:09.278
why do you need
a Girls Who Code?

00:47:09.278 --> 00:47:10.820
Why can't it just
be People Who Code?

00:47:10.820 --> 00:47:12.482
Because we don't
have a Boys Who Code,

00:47:12.482 --> 00:47:13.940
so why do we need
a Girls Who Code?

00:47:13.940 --> 00:47:14.840
RESHMA SAUJANI: And it's
the girls saying it?

00:47:14.840 --> 00:47:16.128
AUDIENCE: Yeah, exactly.

00:47:16.128 --> 00:47:17.670
It was actually a
girl from, I think,

00:47:17.670 --> 00:47:20.210
a comp Sci club, another
comp sci club, saying that.

00:47:20.210 --> 00:47:22.200
But we faced a lot of backlash.

00:47:22.200 --> 00:47:23.270
And I just want to know.

00:47:23.270 --> 00:47:25.440
You probably have
to since the start.

00:47:25.440 --> 00:47:26.690
And how do you deal with that?

00:47:26.690 --> 00:47:28.370
RESHMA SAUJANI:
Yeah, listen, I think

00:47:28.370 --> 00:47:31.420
it's internalized patriarchy.

00:47:31.420 --> 00:47:32.870
It is, right?

00:47:32.870 --> 00:47:35.510
We oftentimes-- I was just
having this conversation

00:47:35.510 --> 00:47:37.190
with a woman last week.

00:47:37.190 --> 00:47:38.600
And she was like, well--

00:47:38.600 --> 00:47:41.540
she was a senior woman in tech
at a very senior company who

00:47:41.540 --> 00:47:43.300
has a son, which I do too.

00:47:43.300 --> 00:47:44.780
And she said, I just think we--

00:47:44.780 --> 00:47:48.140
what about the boys?

00:47:48.140 --> 00:47:49.940
What about the boys?

00:47:49.940 --> 00:47:51.380
What about the boys?

00:47:51.380 --> 00:47:53.090
It's as if we're living in a--

00:47:53.090 --> 00:47:56.460
we can talk about the boys when
we're at 70, and they're at 30.

00:47:56.460 --> 00:47:58.590
And then I'll start
Boys Who Code, right?

00:47:58.590 --> 00:48:00.640
But we're not even close.

00:48:00.640 --> 00:48:02.840
We're not even
touching the surface.

00:48:02.840 --> 00:48:04.790
I think that's
internalized patriarchy.

00:48:04.790 --> 00:48:07.850
I think we're so
raised to be thinking

00:48:07.850 --> 00:48:10.970
about them and their feelings.

00:48:10.970 --> 00:48:13.370
And I think we so still--

00:48:13.370 --> 00:48:16.520
I still remember middle
school teenage freshmen who

00:48:16.520 --> 00:48:20.240
wanted to be liked by the boys.

00:48:20.240 --> 00:48:22.340
We want them to accept us.

00:48:22.340 --> 00:48:25.340
And so in certain ways
by wanting them to accept

00:48:25.340 --> 00:48:26.930
us means that we
have to deny things

00:48:26.930 --> 00:48:30.290
that are beneficial to us.

00:48:30.290 --> 00:48:32.700
We need to have
these conversations.

00:48:32.700 --> 00:48:34.200
We need to have
these conversations.

00:48:34.200 --> 00:48:35.840
I'm obviously a
political junkie,

00:48:35.840 --> 00:48:41.990
but it drives me nuts,
nuts, that so many women

00:48:41.990 --> 00:48:43.340
voted for him.

00:48:43.340 --> 00:48:46.070
And that yet again,
they will do it again--

00:48:46.070 --> 00:48:50.820
except black women,
except black women.

00:48:50.820 --> 00:48:54.460
And what is that about?

00:48:54.460 --> 00:48:57.230
But we don't have these
conversations as women.

00:48:57.230 --> 00:48:59.690
And we have to.

00:48:59.690 --> 00:49:00.630
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:49:00.630 --> 00:49:02.050
JASON SPERO: Thank you.

00:49:02.050 --> 00:49:03.050
AUDIENCE: All right, hi.

00:49:03.050 --> 00:49:04.500
I'm from the same club.

00:49:04.500 --> 00:49:07.550
And so as a high school
student, obviously, you

00:49:07.550 --> 00:49:09.945
need drive to keep
going forward.

00:49:09.945 --> 00:49:10.820
I was just wondering.

00:49:10.820 --> 00:49:14.060
How do you find motivation
on day-to-day basis

00:49:14.060 --> 00:49:16.910
to take your foundation
to the next level

00:49:16.910 --> 00:49:19.618
to do something no
one's ever done before?

00:49:19.618 --> 00:49:21.410
Where do you find the
pride and motivation?

00:49:21.410 --> 00:49:24.560
RESHMA SAUJANI: Yeah, listen,
I feel like we say in Hinduism.

00:49:24.560 --> 00:49:25.400
What's your dharma?

00:49:25.400 --> 00:49:27.680
What are you put on
this earth to do?

00:49:27.680 --> 00:49:30.087
And I've always had
a very strong sense--

00:49:30.087 --> 00:49:31.670
I know this is going
to sound cheesy--

00:49:31.670 --> 00:49:35.340
but I love this country.

00:49:35.340 --> 00:49:38.660
I love this country.

00:49:38.660 --> 00:49:42.200
And I want to do what is best.

00:49:42.200 --> 00:49:46.140
And I also know my parents came
here as refugees with nothing.

00:49:46.140 --> 00:49:47.300
I've been a dog walker.

00:49:47.300 --> 00:49:51.950
I've worked at Baskin-Robbins,
retail, telemarketer.

00:49:51.950 --> 00:49:55.310
And I see far too
many of my students

00:49:55.310 --> 00:49:59.900
that are just being left behind,
who have like one meal a day

00:49:59.900 --> 00:50:01.918
and will go from Oakland
to Facebook or Google

00:50:01.918 --> 00:50:03.710
to learn how to code
because they just want

00:50:03.710 --> 00:50:06.360
a shot at the American dream.

00:50:06.360 --> 00:50:10.670
And I think that I and
we have an opportunity

00:50:10.670 --> 00:50:12.840
to make things
different for them.

00:50:12.840 --> 00:50:15.590
And so I wake up every
day thinking about them

00:50:15.590 --> 00:50:20.630
and about like that I feel so
blessed that I, in my lifetime,

00:50:20.630 --> 00:50:23.746
can make one
person's life better.

00:50:23.746 --> 00:50:27.050
AUDIENCE: All right, thank you.

00:50:27.050 --> 00:50:28.380
AUDIENCE: Hi, I'm Sonia.

00:50:28.380 --> 00:50:30.260
I'm also from the same club.

00:50:30.260 --> 00:50:32.390
So this is really amazing.

00:50:32.390 --> 00:50:34.200
I didn't think that
this would be possible.

00:50:34.200 --> 00:50:40.400
But as a high school student,
I find it really difficult

00:50:40.400 --> 00:50:44.300
to be motivated to
jump at opportunities

00:50:44.300 --> 00:50:48.090
which I'd be scared I'd fail
at and take these risks.

00:50:48.090 --> 00:50:53.600
So what inspires you
to wake up one day

00:50:53.600 --> 00:50:59.120
and make the transformation
from go-getter to gutsy?

00:50:59.120 --> 00:51:01.880
RESHMA SAUJANI: I just
don't want to be--

00:51:01.880 --> 00:51:03.060
and I say this.

00:51:03.060 --> 00:51:03.560
I'm 43.

00:51:03.560 --> 00:51:04.060
I know.

00:51:04.060 --> 00:51:05.300
Why am I outing myself?

00:51:05.300 --> 00:51:05.840
But I will.

00:51:05.840 --> 00:51:06.340
[LAUGHTER]

00:51:06.340 --> 00:51:12.790
So I see a lot of women in my
life that are just unhappy,

00:51:12.790 --> 00:51:16.720
and they didn't do the things
that they wanted to do.

00:51:16.720 --> 00:51:18.670
And they're bitter.

00:51:18.670 --> 00:51:20.715
And I don't want to be that.

00:51:20.715 --> 00:51:22.090
I don't want to
be sitting there.

00:51:22.090 --> 00:51:23.923
That's why I make myself,
once a year, think

00:51:23.923 --> 00:51:25.480
about running for office again.

00:51:25.480 --> 00:51:27.700
Just to check myself, right?

00:51:27.700 --> 00:51:29.500
Because I don't want
to be sitting there

00:51:29.500 --> 00:51:34.060
and regret a life never lived.

00:51:34.060 --> 00:51:36.190
And that's what also gets me up.

00:51:36.190 --> 00:51:37.510
I also feel like--

00:51:37.510 --> 00:51:40.120
I think sometimes,
for many of us,

00:51:40.120 --> 00:51:42.520
I don't know if I know
what I like anymore

00:51:42.520 --> 00:51:44.980
or whether I've told myself
that I don't like something

00:51:44.980 --> 00:51:46.990
because I wasn't good at it.

00:51:46.990 --> 00:51:48.660
And I don't want to miss out.

00:51:48.660 --> 00:51:53.020
I have a husband who lives life
to his fullest, as Jason knows.

00:51:53.020 --> 00:51:56.110
And he lives his
life that way, right?

00:51:56.110 --> 00:51:58.540
And I see how much
joy it brings him.

00:51:58.540 --> 00:51:59.740
You don't see guys like--

00:51:59.740 --> 00:52:01.660
this isn't a management book.

00:52:01.660 --> 00:52:04.090
Don't read this book if
you want a promotion.

00:52:04.090 --> 00:52:06.580
Read this book if
you want to be happy,

00:52:06.580 --> 00:52:08.590
if you want to be
joyful, if you want

00:52:08.590 --> 00:52:11.530
to live your life with
the full gusto of the way

00:52:11.530 --> 00:52:13.520
we should live our lives.

00:52:13.520 --> 00:52:15.250
And that's what I want.

00:52:15.250 --> 00:52:18.110
And that's what I want for
each and every one of you.

00:52:18.110 --> 00:52:21.310
And I think when we do that,
all these leadership numbers,

00:52:21.310 --> 00:52:23.318
all this stuff of like
taking the world over--

00:52:23.318 --> 00:52:24.610
because I want to do that too--

00:52:24.610 --> 00:52:26.200
that's all going to come.

00:52:26.200 --> 00:52:29.185
Because we're going to come
at it from a different spirit.

00:52:29.185 --> 00:52:30.060
AUDIENCE: Hey, there.

00:52:30.060 --> 00:52:30.680
I'm Eva.

00:52:30.680 --> 00:52:31.972
I'm an engineer here at Google.

00:52:31.972 --> 00:52:34.377
Thanks a lot for coming
out to speak with us.

00:52:34.377 --> 00:52:35.210
I've got a question.

00:52:35.210 --> 00:52:39.020
So what advice do you have for
those of us who are in industry

00:52:39.020 --> 00:52:43.490
and would really like to make
a connection with the younger

00:52:43.490 --> 00:52:46.420
generation of girls that
want to get into coding, that

00:52:46.420 --> 00:52:49.770
want to establish friendships,
mentorships, things like that?

00:52:49.770 --> 00:52:51.800
There is a typical
check the website thing.

00:52:51.800 --> 00:52:54.050
But just kind of beyond that,
do you have any thoughts

00:52:54.050 --> 00:52:55.008
on how to get involved?

00:52:55.008 --> 00:52:57.830
RESHMA SAUJANI: You should be
giving back every single day.

00:52:57.830 --> 00:52:59.690
And you should judge
yourself for that.

00:52:59.690 --> 00:53:01.550
You really should, seriously.

00:53:01.550 --> 00:53:03.330
And I actually think that--

00:53:03.330 --> 00:53:04.880
I mean, I don't
know you, but I'm

00:53:04.880 --> 00:53:07.220
sure you have an
incredible story.

00:53:07.220 --> 00:53:10.250
And so much for them, they just
want to hear how you did it.

00:53:10.250 --> 00:53:11.150
Like, what did you--

00:53:11.150 --> 00:53:13.190
what are the doubts that
you had in your head?

00:53:13.190 --> 00:53:15.352
What's the knowledge
that you shared?

00:53:15.352 --> 00:53:16.310
You have to understand.

00:53:16.310 --> 00:53:20.120
So much of, I think, power
and success, as I've realized,

00:53:20.120 --> 00:53:22.343
is knowledge sharing.

00:53:22.343 --> 00:53:25.010
Even if you told them, hey, when
you go into a Google interview,

00:53:25.010 --> 00:53:26.450
this is what to expect.

00:53:26.450 --> 00:53:28.160
This is what they're
going to ask you.

00:53:28.160 --> 00:53:30.313
These are the tricks
and trades, right?

00:53:30.313 --> 00:53:31.730
This is the things
that I doubted.

00:53:31.730 --> 00:53:33.530
Don't do this, or do this.

00:53:33.530 --> 00:53:35.757
Sharing knowledge,
you have knowledge.

00:53:35.757 --> 00:53:37.340
All of us in this
room have knowledge.

